title: Memphis
on-arrival: lbj_ev_mlk = 1; lbj_racial_tension += 25; lbj_unity -= 15; lbj_liberals -= 8; lbj_far_right += 6; lbj_antiwar += 8
go-to: lbj_ev_mlk_scene

@lbj_ev_mlk_scene
title: Memphis, April 4
new-page: true

The phone call comes at 8:20 p.m.

Martin Luther King Jr. has been shot on the balcony of the Lorraine Motel in Memphis, Tennessee. He was there supporting striking sanitation workers. He is dead.

You sit with this for a moment. You have known King for years. You have agreed with him on some things and argued with him on others and you are aware, in the specific way you are aware of things you don't examine too carefully, that the relationship between you was never simple.

He was thirty-nine years old.

The cities are about to burn. You can already hear it starting — the reports coming in from Chicago, from Washington, from Baltimore. You have to decide what to say before the fires spread, and what you say will matter, and there is nothing you can say that is sufficient.

- @lbj_ev_mlk_respond_grace: Address the nation. Ask for peace. Make it personal.
- @lbj_ev_mlk_respond_order: Mobilize the National Guard immediately. Order first.
- @lbj_ev_mlk_respond_legislation: Announce you are pushing the Fair Housing Act in his name.

@lbj_ev_mlk_respond_grace
title: The Address
on-arrival: lbj_racial_tension -= 6; lbj_unity += 4; lbj_liberals += 5; lbj_credibility += 3

You speak for eleven minutes. You do not use a teleprompter.

You say that America is shocked and saddened. You say that Martin Luther King dedicated his life to love and to justice between fellow human beings. You say that this is a time of national tragedy. You say you ask every citizen to reject the blind violence that has struck down Dr. King.

Thirty-nine cities will have riots in the days that follow. Forty-six people will die. You walk the burning streets of Washington with aides who are frightened and you are not frightened exactly but you are something.

The riots stop. The grief does not.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_ev_mlk_respond_order
title: National Guard
on-arrival: lbj_racial_tension -= 4; lbj_unity -= 2; lbj_liberals -= 6; lbj_far_right -= 4; lbj_south_backlash -= 3

You mobilize fifty-five thousand National Guard and Army troops in the days that follow. The fires go out. The streets quiet. It is described as restoring order. It is also described as an occupation.

The photographs of soldiers on the steps of the Capitol building will circulate for years.

Order is a form of something. Not peace. But order.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_ev_mlk_respond_legislation
title: In His Name
on-arrival: lbj_cr_progress += 1; lbj_capital -= 14; lbj_liberals += 8; lbj_racial_tension -= 5; lbj_dixiecrats -= 7

You call the Speaker within an hour of the announcement. You tell him the Fair Housing Act is going to the floor this week. You do not ask.

It passes within a week. The Fair Housing Act of 1968, prohibiting discrimination in the sale and rental of most housing in the United States.

You sign it on April 11. The pen is heavy.

You say: *"We have passed many civil rights laws. They alone are not enough. Justice for all our people cannot wait."*

You mean it. It is not enough. You mean that too.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

