# SCRIPTED EVENT: Chicago 1968 Convention
# =============================================================================

@lbj_ev_chicago_trigger
title: Chicago
on-arrival: lbj_ev_chicago = 1; lbj_unity -= 10; lbj_liberals -= 15; lbj_antiwar -= 8; lbj_labor -= 5; lbj_credibility -= 8; lbj_far_right += 8
go-to: lbj_ev_chicago_scene

@lbj_ev_chicago_scene
title: Grant Park, August 1968
new-page: true

The Democratic National Convention is in Chicago.

Mayor Daley has the city locked down. Twenty-three thousand law enforcement. Barbed wire around the convention hall. The demonstrators are in Grant Park — ten, fifteen thousand of them — and they are chanting things and the police are moving on them with clubs and the television cameras are everywhere.

Inside the hall, the delegates are nominating Hubert Humphrey, your Vice President, your loyal Hubert, who has spent four years defending policies he privately disagreed with because that is what loyalty required.

The country is watching Grant Park. The country is watching the police. The country is watching itself.

You are watching it from the White House. You chose not to attend your own party's convention.

- @lbj_ev_chicago_condemn: Condemn the police violence publicly.
- @lbj_ev_chicago_support: Support Daley. Order must be maintained.
- @lbj_ev_chicago_silent: Say nothing. It is Daley's city.

@lbj_ev_chicago_condemn
title: Too Far
on-arrival: lbj_liberals += 6; lbj_labor -= 6; lbj_far_right += 5; lbj_credibility += 4; lbj_unity -= 3

You break with Daley. You say publicly that the use of force against peaceful demonstrators was excessive. Daley does not speak to you for three weeks.

The statement matters to some people. It does not stop what is already happening.

Humphrey loses in November. The question of whether your statement helped or hurt is not one the historians will agree on.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_ev_chicago_support
title: Law and Order
on-arrival: lbj_labor += 3; lbj_liberals -= 12; lbj_far_right -= 5; lbj_credibility -= 8; lbj_unity -= 5

You back Daley. Order, you say, must be maintained.

The footage runs on television for days. Your backing of Daley runs alongside it.

You will spend years explaining what you meant. You will not fully succeed.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue

@lbj_ev_chicago_silent
title: No Comment
on-arrival: lbj_credibility -= 5; lbj_liberals -= 7; lbj_unity -= 4

Your silence is read as endorsement by some and cowardice by others.

Both interpretations have some evidence for them.

- @lbj_main_hand: Continue


# =============================================================================
# THE PERSONAL DECK
# LBJ as a man — the private decisions, the late nights, the cost
# =============================================================================

@lbj_personal_lady_bird
title: Lady Bird
is-card: true
card-image: img/ladybird_card.png
tags: lbj_personal_card
max-visits: 5

She is the only person in the world who tells you the truth directly and without an agenda.

She does not do it publicly — she is too skilled a political partner for that. But in the residence, late, when the day has been the kind of day that the job produces with regularity, she says the things that need saying.

Tonight she says: *"Lyndon. You look tired in a way that rest isn't going to fix."*

You tell her you're fine.

She waits.

- @lbj_personal_ladybird_listen: Listen. Actually listen.
- @lbj_personal_ladybird_deflect: Tell her what you always tell her: it's the job.

@lbj_personal_ladybird_listen
title: She's Right
on-arrival: lbj_paranoia -= 5; lbj_capital += 3; lbj_approval += 1; lbj_jfk_shadow -= 5

You stop. You sit down at the kitchen table in the residence and you actually listen to what she is telling you, which is: you are carrying too much of this inside. The war is in you. The deaths are in you. The decisions you've made that you can't take back are in you.

She doesn't say any of this in so many words. She doesn't have to.

You talk until past midnight. You sleep better than you have in weeks.

In the morning the problems are all still there. But you are slightly more able to carry them.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_personal_ladybird_deflect
title: It's the Job
on-arrival: lbj_paranoia += 3; lbj_jfk_shadow += 3

You say it's the job and you're fine and she should go to sleep.

She goes to sleep. You stay up for another two hours reading cables.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: The 2 A.M. Call from Vietnam
# =============================================================================

@lbj_personal_2am
title: 2 A.M.
is-card: true
card-image: img/phone_night_card.png
tags: lbj_personal_card
view-if: lbj_vietnam >= 20
max-visits: 6

The secure phone rings.

It is the overnight military watch officer. A situation in the Delta. Numbers. You take the numbers down on a pad and you will throw the pad away in the morning.

You have been doing this — getting up at 3 a.m. to take these calls — since the escalation began. You get up every night. Some nights there is nothing. Some nights there is something.

You know the name of every man who dies in the first weeks. Later you cannot do this anymore. There are too many.

- @lbj_personal_2am_numbers: Process it. Make the decisions. Go back to sleep.
- @lbj_personal_2am_personal: Ask about the men. Specific men. Make it human.

@lbj_personal_2am_numbers
title: The Arithmetic
on-arrival: lbj_vietnam -= 1; lbj_casualties += 1; lbj_paranoia += 2

You take the numbers and you make the call and you go back to sleep.

In the morning there will be other numbers. The process continues. You are managing a war the way you managed the Senate: one relationship, one phone call, one piece of leverage at a time.

It is not the same. You are beginning to understand it is not the same.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_personal_2am_personal
title: Their Names
on-arrival: lbj_credibility += 2; lbj_paranoia -= 2; lbj_antiwar -= 1; lbj_capital -= 2

You ask the watch officer to stay on the line. You ask him to tell you about the men in the report. Where they were from. What unit.

He does. He is surprised, you can tell, but he does it.

You write down the names. In the morning you will have your office find the next of kin. Not a form letter — you will sign notes personally. You cannot do this for everyone. You do it for these ones.

Moyers finds out. He doesn't say anything. Later he will say something, to a journalist, about who you were when no one was watching.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

# =============================================================================
# CARD: JFK's Shadow
# =============================================================================

@lbj_personal_jfk
title: His Office Now
is-card: true
card-image: img/jfk_card.png
tags: lbj_personal_card
view-if: lbj_jfk_shadow > 40
max-visits: 4

It is still being called the Kennedy administration in some of the press. You read this and you file it. Kennedy's men are mostly still here — McNamara, Bundy, Rusk — and they look at you sometimes with an expression that is impossible to fully read but that you have become very good at approximately reading.

You did not take this office the way a man wants to take an office. You know that. Everyone knows that.

The question is whether you're going to spend your presidency apologizing for it or building something worth apologizing about.

- @lbj_personal_jfk_embrace: Embrace the continuity. Build on what he started.
- @lbj_personal_jfk_own: Make it your own. Enough with the Kennedy administration.
- @lbj_personal_jfk_obsess: Let it drive you. Prove something.

@lbj_personal_jfk_embrace
title: Continuity
on-arrival: lbj_jfk_shadow -= 10; lbj_liberals += 5; lbj_capital += 3; lbj_credibility += 2

You call it what it is: you are continuing the work. The tax cut. The civil rights bill. The Alliance for Progress. You are not replacing Kennedy; you are completing him.

This framing costs you something personally. It also gets you something politically. The Kennedy loyalists — and there are many — begin to see you as custodian rather than usurper. It is not affection, but it is less opposition.

The rocking chair stays.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_personal_jfk_own
title: President Johnson
on-arrival: lbj_jfk_shadow -= 15; lbj_liberals -= 3; lbj_capital += 5; lbj_credibility += 3

You begin the long process of making it your own. New people. New programs. The Great Society, which is yours — not continuation, but construction.

Some of the Kennedy people leave. They leave gracefully; this is Washington and everyone understands transitions.

The rocking chair is moved to the library.

You feel, for the first time, that this is your office.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

@lbj_personal_jfk_obsess
title: Enough
on-arrival: lbj_jfk_shadow += 5; lbj_paranoia += 6; lbj_credibility -= 3; lbj_approval -= 2; lbj_gs_progress += 1

You cannot let it go. You are aware you cannot let it go. This awareness does not help.

You push harder on the Great Society — harder than is politically wise, harder than your capital supports — because you are trying to prove something to a dead man and to the people who loved that dead man and to yourself.

Some of what you build in this mode will be the best work of your presidency. Rage, sometimes, builds things.

- @lbj_main_hand: Back to the Oval Office

